<div style="-webkit-text-size-adjust: none; font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', Times, serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4; text-align: left; color: #2D2B19;"><!-- Start feature title -->
<h2 style="color: #161400; margin-top: 0; padding-bottom: 0; padding-top: 0; font-weight: 700; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 28px; line-height: 32px; margin-bottom: 16px;">
<a href="https://www.rand.org/pubs/research_reports/RRA3821-1.html??cutoff=true&amp;utm_source=AdaptiveMailer&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_campaign=7014N000001SnimQAC&amp;utm_term=00v4N00000X4BbbQAF&amp;org=1674&amp;lvl=100&amp;ite=297416&amp;lea=548321&amp;ctr=0&amp;par=1&amp;trk=a0wQK00000CZAOzYAP" style="-webkit-text-size-adjust: none; color: #161400; text-decoration: none;">
<span style="color: #161400; text-decoration: none;">
China’s Leadership Speaks in Code
</span>
</a>
</h2>
<!-- End feature title -->
<!-- Feature blurb -->
<p style="-webkit-text-size-adjust: none; color: #2D2B19; font-family: Georgia, Times, serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 22px; margin: 0; padding: 0; margin-bottom: 20px;">Chinese Communist Party leaders communicate in slogans, linguistic formulations, and key phrases collectively called <em>tifa</em>. These coded messages are used to convey policy directives to party bureaucrats. In a new report, RAND’s Howard Wang outlines the main characteristics of <em>tifa</em>, how it’s used, and what all this illustrates about China’s thinking.
</p><p style="-webkit-text-size-adjust: none; color: #2D2B19; font-family: Georgia, Times, serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 22px; margin: 0; padding: 0; margin-bottom: 16px;">Wang concludes that analyzing <em>tifa</em> can reveal key insights into “what the party tells itself it is doing and why.” Such insights are increasingly important to understanding the party under Chinese President Xi Jinping's leadership and could prove “enormously consequential for U.S. policy.”</p>
